      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary hemolysis QoI validation — CFD vs. experimental NIH index",
      "description": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values from the CFD model were evaluated across the five CPB operating points (flow rates 2–6 L/min, rotational speeds 2000–3500 RPM). The Giersiepen power-law damage accumulation model was applied to Lagrangian particle tracks to compute NIH per operating condition. Simulation results show NIH values in the range 0.0012–0.0048 g/100 L, consistent with values reported in the Bludszuweit (1995) benchmark and the Fraser et al. (2012) centrifugal pump dataset. The worst-case operating point (6 L/min, 3500 RPM) yields NIH = 0.0048 g/100 L, which falls below the RH < 1 acceptance threshold relative to the predicate device. Agreement between simulation and reference data is characterized as satisfactory for the purposes of this assessment.",
      "quantityOfInterest": "Normalized index of hemolysis (NIH, g/100 L)",
      "agreementMetric": "Relative hemolysis index RH = NIH_device / NIH_predicate < 1.0",
      "outcomeStatement": "All five operating points satisfy RH < 1; worst-case NIH within range of published centrifugal pump data.",
      "validationStatus": "assessed"
    },
