      "rationale": "Inlet boundary conditions (flow rates 2–6 L/min, impeller speeds 2000–3500 RPM) were set to match the five CPB operating points defined in the COU. Blood analog fluid (glycerol-water, viscosity 3.5 mPa·s at 37°C) properties applied per ASTM F1841. Temperature maintained at 37°C in simulation consistent with normothermic CPB. Gradation 2 conditions documented and applied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted NIH values compared against experimental reference values; agreement metric (RH) computed and reported for all operating points.",
      "rationale": "NIH predictions were compared against reference values from the Fraser et al. (2012) dataset and the Bludszuweit (1995) benchmark. The Fraser et al. dataset was collected using a magnetically levitated centrifugal pump in a ventricular assist device configuration at flow rates of 3–8 L/min and speeds of 2200–3600 RPM. These operating conditions overlap partially with the CPB range but were acquired under chronic VAD hemodynamic loading rather than acute CPB circuit conditions. RH values computed relative to this dataset range from 0.71 to 0.94 across the five CPB operating points, all satisfying RH < 1. The assessment treats this agreement as confirmation of model adequacy without explicitly noting the VAD-versus-CPB circuit distinction. Gradation 2 output comparison criterion recorded as satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "NIH and RH index are established QoIs for pump hemolysis assessment per ASTM F1841 and ISO 10993-4; direct linkage to clinical hemolysis endpoint documented.",
      "rationale": "NIH is the standard laboratory measure of pump-induced hemolysis per ASTM F1841. The relative hemolysis index RH provides a device-versus-predicate comparison consistent with 510(k) substantial equivalence methodology. Both QoIs are directly traceable to the clinical endpoint (plasma free hemoglobin elevation). Relevance criterion at Gradation 2 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities involve a centrifugal blood pump geometry and operating range that encompass or bound the CPB COU operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation activities used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry under flow and speed conditions spanning 2–6 L/min and 2000–3500 RPM, encompassing the CPB COU operating envelope. Reference experimental data from published centrifugal pump hemolysis studies were used to establish the comparison baseline. The validation hierarchy is judged adequate for Gradation 2 relevance. No explicit reconciliation of CPB circuit impedance characteristics versus VAD afterload conditions was performed, as this distinction was considered outside the scope of the current credibility assessment."
    },
